data.title: Excellent dinner !
data.text:
Big quantity for he breakfast, a lot of choice, excellent for an incredibule price ! 
Service is nice, fast and very friendly.
We will return next time we go to Salinas

data.title: Tasty food and good service
data.text:
We had never eaten at Yang's Cafe, when we walked in for lunch at 12:20 today.  Yang's was busy, with front mostly full, and large party of 20 in the back room.  I cleared a table for us in the corner, and retrieved 2 menus and we sat.  After 5 minutes we had decided on Philly Cheese Steak Sandwich with Sweet Potato Fries, and the Reuben with Potato Salad. After 10 minutes, a waitress came by, got 2 waters and service, and took our order.  She added we were not in her section, but our waitress had the big party by herself. There was a help wanted sign in the window.  The place was busy, and it really needs a steam cleaning from ceiling to floor.  We hoped for good food and we waited some more.

The food was wonderful!  The corned beef was cooked and thick sliced by Sang's.  Corned beef was tender, juicy, and ample.  The rye was grilled just right, the sauerkraut was right on, and the mustard was spicy.  It was awesome.  The potato salad was very good, and I tasted to me like there was bacon in it.  The Philly Cheesesteak Sandwich looked huge, with slices of tender steak.  A different take on Sweet Potato Fries - cubed, roasted (I think), and then into fryer only when ordered.  Tasty, but not like traditional long thin french fry cut.

I commented to the waitress how good the corned beef was, and added, "You cook and slice the corned beef here, don't you?"  She looked surprised, and stated that it was cooked and sliced in the kitchen, 

Overall, the restaurant serves a lot of diners, and it has a look that says that.  A little worn, a little grime, and in need of a serious cleaning.  But the food was good.

data.title: Best breakfast in South Salinas
data.text: If you ever get a chance to go to Sam's Restaurant just know that you're going to get yourself a hearty good old down to earth American style Mia and know that you're going to get food at a reasonable price so check out saying I've never gone there and had a bad experience and I've gone there many times it's a favorite good old breakfast

data.title: First Time Locals
data.text: Shame on us for being locals who have never eaten at the restaurant that John Steinbeck ate at until now. The place looks very small from the street but upon walking in, you realize it extends really far back. The menu is pretty lengthy and I wasn't too hungry so I ordered a light breakfast which was perfect. We will definitely be back!!

data.title: Steinbeck ate here!
data.text: This place is still owned by the same family that ran it when John Steinbeck used to eat there.  It is an authentic American greasy spoon diner and has the all ambiance associated with that.  Big portions and an extensive menu take you back to the 'good old days'.  The food is good and fresh and the service is friendly. definitely a must when visiting Salinas.

data.title: Excellent choice for a great breakfast
data.text:
John Steinbeck used to enjoy breakfast there.  That would be enough to draw me in.
Beyond that, the food is very good...and there is a wide menu...like steak and eggs with 3 kinds of steak.  The atmosphere is home town and the service is very attentive and quick.

data.title: A great find in Salinas
data.text: We decided to visit Sangs after looking for a good breakfast café on TA. We hit the jackpot - a warm welcome, fast service and great fresh food. Full breakfast for $9 - YUM!

data.title: Nice and fast
data.text:
I was impressed how fast was the breakfast come to the table.
Very efficient staff and the food was pretty good.
Nothing can go wrong when you a lot locals eating there.

data.title: Old timers & locals agree - come early; they close before 3.
data.text: Don't come here unless you're hungry - portions are huge.  Extensive menu featuring American & local specialities for breakfast or lunch.  This is comfort food - no diet plates here. Two good problems 1) if you have to return to work following lunch, you will want to have a nice nap should you finish the entire plate so plan on getting a doggie bag, & 2) close to the Maya Cinema & steinbeck Center so could get busy.  don't worry tho - service is quick and the locals help themselves to soup, bread & butter.  If you like prime rib, they offer a special on Wednesday but sell out early.

data.title: Accidental gem
data.text: We visited while waiting for the Steinbeck centre to open and enjoyed the friendly welcoming ambiance and great tea and coffee. The service was lovely taking trouble to find a smaller cup and all was reasonably priced. Recommended.

data.title: Always great food
data.text: Seat yourself and start reading from the tons of choices available on the menu.  The gravy is the best!  We have never been disappointed with Sangs!  Home cooking comfort foods.  Service is quick.  Go hungry because they load your plate full!

data.title: Sunday breakfast
data.text: Delicious! Great service fairly quick service for a Sunday we didn't have to wait for a table. Once we were sat and ordered it became busy but our food was still out quickly. Husband ordered all american breakfast and it was great.   I ordered country steak breakfast. I felt it a bit was bland but the rest was good. As a side i had oat bread and i tried the biscuits and gravy both were super good. Oh! And the hashbrowns were different from others I've had as in better.  Will definitely be coming back.  Service was quick and all the staff was pleasant and attentive.

data.title: Old Town Classic
data.text:
Went in for lunch with a party of 14 ladies. We all ordered something different but I had the Tri-Tip Sandwich and it was really good. Sliced thin but hefty portions of meat in the sandwich along with a good ol' side of French fries that were great too. 

If going for breakfast a must try is the chicken fried steak and gravy or the biscuits and gravy!
Oh and you can't go wrong with any of the omelets :)
Delish!

Plus it's where John Steinbeck used to eat as a kid! Great to know for the tourists visiting the area!

data.title: Sunday breakfast
data.text: This restaurant has been a staple in the Salinas area for many, many years. It boasts, " John Steinbeck ate here".  They recently renovated it so it's cleaner than it usually was. The food is pretty good and reasonably priced. You get quite a bit so be prepared to get a "to go" box.

data.title: Good, American breakfast
data.text:
My cousin and I went here for breakfast looking for a good, regular breakfast and we weren't disappointed.

I got my usual: Ham and cheese omelet with spinach and hash browns. They used real eggs and real chunks of ham and fresh spinach.  The hash browns are more almost like a hash, not the standard hash browns I was used to, but still very very good.  The sourdough bread was the real stuff.  Everything was really good.

The only thing that wasn't the best was the orange juice.  It tasted funny to me, I think because it's fresh squeezed it was a bad batch or oranges.  The waitress took it back and was very nice about it.

I'd come here again!

data.title: Welcome lunch
data.text: Missed out on lunch at Steinbeck's house, so went for where he used to eat. We were the only ones in the cafe and the service was fantastic. I had the standard hamburger. It was huge and cooked to perfection. It was on a great bun and came with avocado, salad and what I call chips (fries). My partner had a vegetarian omelette. The veggie part of it was fresh spinach and mushrooms and avocado. It too was perfectly cooked.The drip filter coffee was fine and kept coming. The water was cold and just what I needed after a few hours in the sun. The serves were big enough to require a take home box. All this for $20.00. Our wait person was cheerful, polite and happy to help us with answers to questions about the food and John Steinbeck's association with the restaurant. Great value.

data.title: BoMb!!!
data.text: Was hella hungover, me& the homie hit up the spot for some roman eggs, feeling like à beast now. Round two tonite.

data.title: Good value for money
data.text: Not a fancy place, but food is always good  like home cooked  big servings. This  restaurant has been a staple in old town salinas for many years.

data.title: Sad to say goodbye
data.text: I adore Sang's and have eaten there scads of times. The food is superb, serving’s huge, great value, excellent service. Steinbeck ate here! The people watching is great and the regulars are always hanging on the stools at the counter. The breakfast menu is like reading a novel. The corned beef hash is homemade and to die for, the biscuits and gravy too! The lamb shanks for lunch are one of my favorites and with at least 12 daily specials to pick from, who needs that book sized menu! The salsa at every table is a bonus used on any meal. All the food comes out of the quintessential greasy spoon kitchen, manned by a family of Chinese cooks all wearing colorful chef’s caps in all kinds of Hawaiian patterns. The foods so damn good you don’t want to look to close at the kitchen. Why the good bye? I’m a nurse and after years of loving this place I got turned off by the cook/cashier, who has some kind of skin disorder on all his fingers. I’m sorry he does and if it’s not contagious, well, it looks bad and grossed me out. Great food, but the cook should be wearing gloves.
